<section class="app-page-shell platform-guide-shell">
    <section class="app-page-header platform-guide-hero">
        <div class="platform-guide-copy">
            <p class="platform-guide-eyebrow">How It Works</p>
            <h1>How HelloUniversity connects public resources, accounts, and role-aware workspaces.</h1>
            <p class="platform-guide-lead">
                This page explains the product flow in plain language so visitors can understand what is public, what requires an account, and why the experience changes by role.
            </p>
            <div class="platform-guide-actions">
                <a href="/features" class="platform-guide-btn platform-guide-btn-primary">View Features</a>
                <a href="/help" class="platform-guide-btn platform-guide-btn-secondary">Open Help Center</a>
            </div>
        </div>

        <aside class="platform-guide-note">
            <p class="platform-guide-note-label">Product Flow</p>
            <h2>Three layers</h2>
            <ul class="platform-guide-note-list">
                <li>Public content and support pages</li>
                <li>Account access and role detection</li>
                <li>Student, teacher, and admin workspaces</li>
            </ul>
        </aside>
    </section>

    <section class="platform-guide-grid">
        <article class="app-panel platform-guide-panel">
            <p class="platform-guide-section-eyebrow">Walkthrough</p>
            <h2>What a visitor sees from first visit onward</h2>
            <div class="platform-guide-step-list">
                <article class="platform-guide-step">
                    <h3>Public layer</h3>
                    <p>The site exposes lessons, articles, about, help, legal pages, and contact information so visitors can understand the platform before authentication.</p>
                </article>
                <article class="platform-guide-step">
                    <h3>Account layer</h3>
                    <p>Login, signup, password reset, and approval-related flows handle access to the role-aware parts of the product.</p>
                </article>
                <article class="platform-guide-step">
                    <h3>Role-aware layer</h3>
                    <p>After sign-in, the destination changes by role so students, teachers, and admins do not share the same operational workspace.</p>
                </article>
                <article class="platform-guide-step">
                    <h3>Content and workflow layer</h3>
                    <p>Lessons, classes, announcements, quizzes, attendance, and records remain connected so the platform works as one academic environment rather than separate disconnected pages.</p>
                </article>
            </div>
        </article>

